Quem de chaldaico sermone in grecum Doxa peritissimus transulit; tandem de erario Emanuelis aductum Eugenius regni Cicilie admiratus transulit in latinum.\" ).", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "At the beginning of the code a long annotiation written by a later hand from the 15th century says, that  Secretum Secretorum was wrongly ascribed to ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Aristoteles", "type": "person", "person": 72}, {"text": ", because  of different thoughts in the text (cf. f. ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1v-1v", "type": "locus_multi", "to_page": 5192, "to_folio": "1v", "from_page": 5192, "from_folio": "1v"}, {"text": " we can find a contemporary list of Contents: \"Commentator de Sensu et sensato / Comm. de memoria  et reminiscentia / Comm. de sompno et vigilia / Comm. de causa longitudinis et brevitatis vite /  (Comm. de morte et vita [added]) / Comm. de vegetabilibus / Themistius (corrected from Simplicius)  super de anima / Comm. super de anima Aristotelis.\" ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "On the same page somebody placed an early price (?)  in red chalk, apparently \"SS d\" and some other notes from the 14th century: \"Liber de inundacione Nili /  de progressu animalium / de motu animalium / de coloribus / de bona fortuna / aliquos istorum habeo,  and one earased.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "On the stub of the leaf formerly conjugate with folio 1 is the beginning of an inscription: \"Dit boe[k ...],  which seems to confirm the Low Country origin suggested by hand and ink (though Lacombe thought the hands of MS 113 English).", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "On f. hand_description: [{"text": "Text is written by multiple hands; according to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library, all Flemish, fine, acute and greatly contracted hands in black ink.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "Section 1 was written by one librarian from western Germany or Flanders, according to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library it is a compressed hand of the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "late 13th century", "type": "text"}, {"text": " with vertical ductus, the scribe of which does not recur.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "Section 2 was written by a western German librarian, if ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "d'Alverny", "type": "person", "person": 388}, {"text": " is not mistaken.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "Sections 3 and 4 were each written by one northern librarian, section 3 in a thin script.", "type": "text"}]
binding_description: [{"text": "According to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library: old oak binding with small folio wormed oak boards and paper back, in a tan book case.", "type": "text"}]
provenance: [{"text": "According to a modern note on flyleaf I, this codex was donated to \"", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Friderico", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " notario\" of the monastery of Admont in ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1376", "type": "text"}, {"text": ". According to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library, it is also included in the inventory of Admont from the same year, with the comment, that the group of codices to which it belongs, were given to the monastery by its notary, ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Dominus Friedericus", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": ". Moreover, according to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library, the Admont number 487 is written on the back and inside of the front cover.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "At a later time, ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Henricus Fletcher", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " legally bought the codex. He bestowed it upon ", "type": "text"}, {"text": ", New York, in ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1951", "type": "text"}, {"text": ". According to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library, ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Ernst Philip Goldschmidt", "type": "person", "person": 165}, {"text": " sold it to ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Fletcher", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " in ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1937", "type": "text"}, {"text": ", after having bought it from the monastery of Admont, and ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Fletcher", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " presented it to ", "type": "text"}, {"text": " in ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "April 1951", "type": "text"}, {"text": ".", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "According to the Curatorial Description of the Morgan Library, ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Ernst Philip Goldschmidt", "type": "person", "person": 165}, {"text": " suggested, that the manuscript was written in Paris, which is corroborated due to its resemblance to textual books produced by scholars at the university, specifically: the German college.", "type": "text"}]
additions: [{"text": "On flyleafs Ir - Iv we have a parchment fragment of a judicial tractate in two columns from the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "14th century", "type": "text"}, {"text": ".", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "On flyleaf Iv, in the margins, we have a summary of the contents by a northern hand from the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "14th century", "type": "text"}, {"text": ": \"In hoc libro continentur libri Metharorum ; Summa naturalium magistri ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Alberti", "type": "person", "person": 40}, {"text": " [this references to item 2, the Philosophia pauperum of ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Albertus de Orlamunda", "type": "person", "person": 43}, {"text": "]; De intellectu et intellecto, et ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Bocius Catus", "type": "person", "person": 107}, {"text": " [sic] de summo bono, et idem de Sompno et vigilia ; et de inuisiblibus Dei ; de necessario et possibili ; et ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Aristotelis", "type": "person", "person": 72}, {"text": " de presagiis tempestatum ; et ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Auerrois", "type": "person", "person": 85}, {"text": " de sensu et sensato ; et idem de memoria et reminiscentia ; et idem de sompno et vigilia ; et idem de causis longeuitatis vite ; et idem super librum de plantis ; et idem de substantia orbis ; de motu cordis\".", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "On f. ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "52v-52v", "type": "locus_multi", "to_page": 0, "to_folio": "52v", "from_page": 0, "from_folio": "52v"}, {"text": " a current hand from the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "14th century", "type": "text"}, {"text": " added: \"Nota quod philosophia naturalis, cum sit de corpore mobili ut de subiecto ... sed tamen in libro de anima non determinat ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Philosophus", "type": "person", "person": 72}, {"text": " aliquid de corpore animato anima rationali, sed de principio huiusmodi corporis, scilicet de anima humana. De corpore vero animato anima rationali, scilicet corpore humano non determinat ibi, sed in libro alio qui dicitur Medicina ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Aristotelis", "type": "person", "person": 72}, {"text": ", qui habetur apud Grecos, et adhuc non est translatus. Deficit nobis, cum sit secta pars scientie naturalis\". ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "On f. ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Lacombe", "type": "person", "person": 194}, {"text": " notes, that after section 1, we have no emendations.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "In section 1 we rarely have emendations, but marginal notes by a contemporary current hand.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "In section 2 we have marginal notes by many current hands from the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "end of the 14th century", "type": "text"}, {"text": ".", "type": "text"}]

provenance: [{"insert": "There is an illegible inscription on the front cover.\nThe codex was made in a French monastery. On f. "}, {"insert": "1v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187283"}}, {"insert": " one can see: \"Philosophia naturalis data Collegio per magistrum Iohannem Wyllisch\", referring to Ioannnes Willisch de Cracovia, who got his \"artium baccalarius\" in Prague in 1401. On postfolio III we have: \"Iste liber obligatus est frater Iohanni Snewelino pro tribus libris ... fratribus de Grisaco\"; and below that: \"Fratris C. Edelini [?] una Biblia parva, qui cum ...\", with added notes on expenses. On the same postfolio, we have a note, apparently referring to a bishop from Płock from the 15th century, indicating, that the codex was in Płock at that time: \"Casimirus Dei gracia episcopus\". On f. "}, {"insert": "128v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187537"}}, {"insert": ", one can see: \"Domini Andree de Florencia, qui moratur coram Simonem [?]\".\n"}]
additions:
[{"insert": "We have extensive margins, written on in a scarcely readable script with pencil around 1300, and glosses by hands from the 14th and 15th century.
The glosses on the Meteorologica follow the commentary of "}, {"insert": "Albert the Great", "attributes": {"color": "#cd5c5c", "person_link": "40"}}, {"insert": ", books I - II being divided into chapters (which was only done in the 15th century).
On f. "}, {"insert": "17v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187315"}}, {"insert": ", one can see "Anna peperit Mariam", and on f. "}, {"insert": "111v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187503"}}, {"insert": " we have a table of the winds. On the same folio, we find: "medium [?] libri, XV folia". F. "}, {"insert": "111r", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187502"}}, {"insert": " has: "[Anima] est actus primus substancialis corporis organici phisici vitam habentis in potencia", with "cyrurgus practicus" above and "Actus insunt substancie", "Genus in sua specie ... homo est animal" below. In the margins of f. "}, {"insert": "129v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187539"}}, {"insert": ", one can see: "Versus. Ingnem [!] Democritus animam fecit"; and on f. "}, {"insert": "152r", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187584"}}, {"insert": ": "Pyramidis. Ex hoc apparet, quod visus semper petit distanciam ...".
On f. "}, {"insert": "199v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "187679"}}, {"insert": " we have a table of contents ("In isto volumine continentur libri subscripti. 1. Liber Phisicorum ... 19. Liber de causis").
"}]

content: [{"insert": "Contains the work \"De compagine membrorum sive de natura humana\" on ff. 97-106. It is ascribed to Averroes by the catalogue by Halm, but this is actually a work by Galen.\n"}]

provenance: [{"text": "This manuscript entered the Sorbonne College before 1307 by the testament of Nicasius (or Nicaise)  of Planca, a Flemish cleric. A member of the college listed it in the obituary as of June 13, in the year 1307. One can read: \"Magister Nicasius de Planca, flamingus, libros naturales in uno volumine et quosdam morales  in alio volumine, qui sunt in catenis, et XL sol. sociis distribuendos\" (cf. f. ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "x1-x1", "type": "locus_multi", "to_page": 30971, "to_folio": "x1", "from_page": 30971, "from_folio": "x1"}, {"text": "). The code is named here as \"libros naturales in uno volumine\" as well as the manuscript Latin 16672  containing Rhetorica, Metaphysica and Physica by ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Aristotle", "type": "person", "person": 72}, {"text": ".  ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "It is said in the statement of the obituary that these manuscripts were chained. The two of them were integrated into the Libraria communis probably from the donation of Nicaise. They appear both in the catalog of 1338 under the category \"cathenatus\" under the heading of  \"Libri naturales not commentati\" with the numbers 32 (Latin 16088) and 33 (Latin 16672).  The mention of librarianship f. decoration: [{"insert": "The first part has tall initial letters in red and blue, with decorating leaves elongated throughout the page. The second part is similiar, but the colours of the littler initial letters are alternating in red and blue and decorated with little colourful points and lines. Furthermore one can find paragraph signs alternating in red and blue. The third part has also taller and smaller initial letters, paragraph signs in red and blue.\n"}]
layout: [{"insert": "The first part has rubrications and annotating voices, some emendations. The second part has some rubrications, emendations and some notes in the margins. collation: [{"insert": "A manuscript out of five parts: I: ff.1-101v, II: ff. 102r-111v, III: ff. 112r-164v, IV: ff. 165r-167v, V: ff. 168r-171v.\n"}]
decoration: [{"insert": "Part I and III have tall initial letters partly red, partly blue. Lines and leaves decorate them in the opposite coulour each. The first part has titles in red and blue at the top of the page. The initials in the second part are small, but decorated with little lines. There are also little paragraph signs. Titles in the third part are written in a cursive handwriting. Initial letters in Part IV and V are not painted but space is left for them.\n"}]
layout: [{"insert": "First part has a lot of emendationes and some notes in the margin. The second part has no rubrications, but titles of chapters are written at the top of some pages. The third part has some emendations and few notes in the margin, made by hands from 14th and 15th century. The fifth part has serveral emendations and notes in the margins of Oeconomica made by a cursive handwriting.\n"}]
hand_description: [{"insert": "Part I and III are made from librarians coming from the mediterrean part of France. Part II is written in a cursive script. Part IV and V are written by one script each, part V again by some cursive writing.\n"}]
binding_description: [{"insert": "The manuscript is bound half with parchment.\n"}]
provenance: [{"insert": "On f. 1r we can find an 18th century seal of the Collège Louis-le-Grand, giving the signature 192, 3, 16. The manuscript also has the old signature \"Ms. l. III, 9\".\n"}]
additions: [{"insert": "\n"}]
origin: [{"insert": "Part I / III / IV: 14th century, part II / V: 15th century.\n"}]

additions:
[{"insert": "Lacombe compares the Aristotelian Text with the Translatio vetus and the Translatio nova and points out that there are diferences.He supposes that it is a compound of both. 
Translation of this code: "Quoniam corporum hoc quidem simplex est, hoc quodem compositum ex simplici, et est dicere corpus simplex omne corpus in quo est principium motus naturalis, verbi gratia ignis et terra et similia formis eorum... "
Translation vetus: "Item etiam dico quod quedam corpora sunt simplicia et quedam composita ex simplicibus. Et non significo per corpus simplex nisi omne corpus in quo est principium motus naturalis sicut ignis et terra et que sunt secundum utrorumque formas..." (Taken from Ambrosian Code, S 70 Sup, f.165r).
Translatio nova: "Quoniam autem corporum hec quidem sunt simplicia, hec autem composita ex hiis, dico autem simplicia quecumque motus primos habeant secundum naturam, puta ignem et terram et horum species et cognata huiis..." (Taken from Padua, Bibl. Univ. 1483, f. 56r).
"}]
content: [{"insert": "Aristoteles' text is pure, but it is uncertain, which translation it is. Lacombe thinks the first part combines parts of both translation, while it follows neither consistently.\n"}]

provenance: [{"text": "Three 14th-cent. inscriptions in a current script on the verso-page of the first original flyleave: 1. \"Liber M. Willhelmi Red  ex dono magistri Nicholai de Sandwyco / Commentum Averois super 8 libris phyisicorum\"; 2. following on this  and now erased, apparently \"Proprietas domus Mertone\", same as in Merton College MS. 282. If this  inscription is correctly read, the volume must have been originally selected as one of the 100 books  left to Merton College by William Rede, who was bishop of Chichester 1368-85, and then transferred to  Balliol by a change of plan. Nicholas of Sandwich was Rede's benefactor. The Balliol inscription is  probably in the hand of Rede's secretary, Walter Roberts. 3. \"Liber aule Balioli Oxon' in communi  libraria eiusdem et ad usum communem sociorum ibidem / studencium cathenandus Ex dono venerabilis patris domini Willheilmi tercii episcopi Cicestrensis. Oretis / iogitur pro eodem et benefactoribus eiusdem ac  fidelium animabus a purgatio liberandis\".", "type": "text"}]

", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "The person of the scribe could not be identified.  His familiy, the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Ghāfiqī", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " was widely spread in Arabic ", "type": "text"}, {"text": ". With certainty an older  relative of the scribe was ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Abū Muḥammad ʿAbdalkabīr b. Muḥammad al-Ghāfiqī", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " -  ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1142 (536 h.)", "type": "text"}, {"text": " - ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1220 (617 h.)", "type": "text"}, {"text": " -,  a scholar of fiqh and ḥadīth who was born near ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Ronda", "type": "text"}, {"text": " and moved to ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Seville", "type": "text"}, {"text": " later on. If we consider the extreme rareness of the name \"", "type": "text"}, {"text": "ʿAbdalkabīr", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": "\" it seems possible - according to  ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "G. Schoeler", "type": "person", "person": 222}, {"text": " (Catalogue p. 124) - that this scholar is nobody  else than the grandfather of our scribe. ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "Schoeler", "type": "person", "person": 222}, {"text": "  assumes consequently that the sribes father was born about ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1172 (568 h.)", "type": "text"}, {"text": " (when the scholar ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "ʿAbdalkabīr b. Muḥammad", "type": "person", "person": null}, {"text": " was  about 30 years old) and concludes that the scribe himself in turn was born about ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "1202 (598 h.)", "type": "text"}, {"text": " (again 30 years later). Therefore the  manuscript must have been written in the first half or - at the latest - in the mid of the ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "13th / 7th h. century", "type": "text"}, {"text": ". ", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "As for the manuscript's text the scribe noted on f. origin: [{"insert": "According to the Incipit of the preface to this collection on fol. "}, {"insert": "1r,", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "171434"}}, {"insert": " the manuscript was produced in Marseilles.\nThe dating is disputed: Whereas the online catalogue of the NLI dates the manuscript to the 15th century (cf. http://merhav.nli.org.il/permalink/f/ldj0th/NNL_ALEPH21290465210005171), the codicological database SfarData, which is based on the work of Malachi Beit-Aryeh, dates it to the second half of the 14th century (cf. Sfardata Record Key : ZB114). This is also the dating followed by Berman, A Manuscript Named \"Shshan Limmudim\"…, p. 368, note 2, who localises the manuscript in a circle of scholars (meʿayyenim) that purportedly had formed around"}, {"insert": " Samuel ben Judah of Marseilles", "attributes": {"color": "#cd5c5c", "person_link": "547"}}, {"insert": ". However, one of the texts contained in this manuscript mentions (fol. "}, {"insert": "130v", "attributes": {"color": "#00aa88", "folio_link": "171693"}}, {"insert": ", lines 8–9) Kalonymos [=Crescas] ben Isaac Nathan of Marseilles, a son of the rich community leader and scholar Isaac Nathan of Arles (cf. Stouff, Isaac Nathan et les siens), and actually calls him \"head of the scholars\" (roʾš ha-meʿayyenim). He was active in the middle of the 15th century and, in fact, is known to have settled in Marseilles around 1446 (cf. the document published in Revue des études juives 48 (1904), pp. 66–73, where it says on p. 69: \"Et magister Crescas Natani, filius dicti Isaac Natani, qui denuo se habitavit in dicta civitate Massilie…\"; for this and further references cf. Ernest Wickersheimer, Dictionnaire biographique des médecins en France au Moyen Âge, Paris 1979, p. 111). Thus it is virtually certain that the manuscript was produced not earlier than the middle of the 15th century.\n"}]

provenance: [{"text": "Owners: Shimshon Kohen Modon, 5459 = 1699, who added marg. notes to the last two treatises, as well as the contents of the MS., according to which two treatises - a. ספר העגולות לבטלמיוס העתקת הרש׳ בן תבון; b. ספר מאזני העיונים (לא נזכר שם פועלו והוא מחמד מאד). Isaya Bassan (at end Rom. char.).", "type": "text"}]
additions: [{"text": "Item 1: With marg. notes, ontaining chiefly omissions and variations (to be read in the preface ספר הנכבד instead of ספר הנפש). After the words אחרי הפרדה מן הגוף (ed. of Venice, fol. 59c) the MS. has וראוי לדעת סבת המחלוקת אשר נחלק בו החכמים הקודמים בהשארות הנפש ואחר כן נסאר ראיותיהם. Next comes a long chapter on the same subject, wherein the opinions of Alexander Aphrodiensis, Themistius, el-Farabi, and Averroes are given, followed by the printed § מאמר לחכם הראשון המכונה ב״ר. The 13th chapter of the edition is not in the MS.", "type": "text"}, {"text": "null", "type": "paragraph"}, {"text": "Item 7: The translator adds a large number of notes, wherein he polemises against the author, smetimes in abusive terms.", "type": "text"}]
